@ellie. Thanks for joining us today. Look at the labels on each axis.  Is it about appeal or volume of food?  Or is it about something else.

Though your comment makes me wonder if people associate 'healthy' with 'doesn't taste good'

Can you think of a good headline for the graph?

@Dorin

It isn't just 40% of nutritionists who say butter is healthy, 40% of average Americans do too!

Was butter the item that made you think of differences by state? Are there things in Great Neck that people think are healthy that people in other areas might disagree?

@Jordan Flores

You mention mass marketing and I think that is an interesting point to consider. Do you think mass marketing is the reason why the average American thinks granola is good for you but nutritionists not so much...

Come back Friday, when we will reveal the free link to the article that includes this graph!

@Landon

WoW! None of the healthy foods are served at your school? That's not ideal. Is it all 'junk food?' Or do they serve things that fall under 'all Americans' think it is healthy, but nutritionists do not?

I wonder, do you think it is because 'healthy' food doesn't sell as well? Or perhaps healthy foods cost more?

@Kyle and Keith

You pick up on a good point on the incomplete data on the responders.  The text of this week's feature states that Morning Consult surveyed 2000 registered voters.  Are you proposing that registered voters may skew to a different view of what is healthy compared to nonregistered voters?  Could be, but what makes you say that? 

There is certainly evidence of a divergence in thoughts between nutritionists and what the poll deemed "All Americans" I wonder what you think accounts for those differences...
